Haven Avenue, east side, from 173rd to 176th Streets. The house in the foreground is the old farmhouse of A. F. Smith, who had a six and one-half acre farm here. The main body of the house probably does not antedate 1870, although it was preceded by an earlier structure on the same site. The little brick wing on the south was added between 1902 and 1910. The little house farther along on the avenue is the modernized house standing on the old Howland farm, which adjoined the Smith farm on the north. The apartment houses beyond, on the S.E. corner of 176th Street, were built around 1924. Around 1910, Haven Avenue used to be known as Buena Vista Avenue. May 27, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

The same, more than seven years later. The two old houses have been demolished; and the land is being cleared and made over into a park to be called J. Hood Wright Park. October 30, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

Riverside Drive, south from a point on a line with West 177th Street (left) showing the area to the south of the new George Washington Bridge (approaches under construction at this date). The apartment houses appearing on the bluff face on Haven Avenue.

Note the frame dwelling remaining. This is between 173rd and 175th Streets and stands in (present) J. Hood Wright Park. For individual pictures of same, see files under that classification.

To the extreme right appears the white buildings comprising the Cornell University--Presbyterian Hospital Center (Cornell Medical Center).

Sept. 29, 1931
P. L. Sperr, photographer
